result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.descr: Records of prosec. are converted data. See file.

records.addlTxt: ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and without counsel.  Defendant still wishes to proceed without counsel.  Defendant plead guilty to Count 1, misdemeanor battery.  Count 2 dismissed, but read in for sentencing purposes.  Court recited the charges and possible penalties on the count he plead to.  Defendant understood.  Court reviewed the plea questionnaire, constitutional rights and elements with the defendant.  Defendant stipulated that there is a factual basis for the plea.   Court found that the defendant freely, voluntarily, and intelligently entered his plea and waived his constitutional rights.  Court found that a factual basis exists for the plea.  Finding witheld, diversion agreement approved.  Court questioned the defendant on his understanding of the diversion agreement.  He stated he understood the agreement, and can comply with the requirements in the agreement. Bond continued.
Tried calling defendant at his cell phone number in court file to let him know that PLEAH has been rescheduled, but his voice mail has not been set up.
Plea hearing on August 15, 2016 at 10:00 am.
Per telephone conference with ADA Inlow and defendant, STC canceled and set for PLEAH.
Plea hearing on July 25, 2016 at 01:30 pm.

Pre-trial conference on June 8, 2016 at 10:00 am.
Status conference on June 27, 2016 at 03:00 pm.
Reading of the complaint waived.  Defendant entered NGP.  Court entered NGP on defendant's behalf.  PTC set for 6/8 and STC set for 6/27 at 3 pm.

Court questioned defendant on his understanding of the waiver.  Court recited the charges and possible penalties contained in the complaint.  Defendant stated he understood.  Court found that defendant knowingly and intelligently waived his right to attorney.
ADA Melissa Inlow appeared for the State.  Defendant appeared in person and without counsel.  Defendant will represent himself.  Waiver of right to attorney form given to the defendant to complete.
